{{Politics of Senegal}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Senegal]] on 20 March 2016. The proposed changes to the constitution were approved by 62% of voters. A majority voted in favour in thirteen of the fourteen [[regions of Senegal|regions]], with only [[Diourbel Region]] seeing a majority against.<ref>[http://koaci.com/senegal-referendum-lemporter-avec-plus-vers-recours-didrissa-seck-thies-96967.html Sénégal: Référendum, le OUI va l'emporter avec plus de 60%, vers un recours d'Idrissa Seck à Thiès] Koaci, 22 March 2016</ref>
==Background== A total of 15 changes were proposed to the constitution, including:<ref name=BBC>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-35854768 Voters in Benin, Cape Verde, Congo, Niger, Senegal and Zanzibar go to polls] BBC News, 20 March 2016</ref> *Shortening of the presidential term from seven years to five years. Contrary to incumbent president [[Macky Sall]]'s wishes, this would only apply from the next presidential election in 2019 onwards.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/senegal-president-macky-sall-power-until-2019-after-failing-shorten-term-1544343 Senegal: President Macky Sall in power until 2019 after failing to shorten term] International Business Times, 17 February 2016</ref> *Constitutional recognition for the Leader of the Opposition *Enhanced powers for local authorities *Rights to a healthy environment *Changes to rights on land ownership and natural resources
